Quantified Self: Sleep Time and Screen Time

Raphael Xie

2023-02-27

A Short Overview about the Project

About the “Self” in this study:
I have Irregular sleep pattern & sleep deprivation ( < 7 hrs), and I rarely fall asleep before midnight (11:59 pm) Heavy phone user (usually > 7 hrs / day).

Purpose of the study:
Analyze the relationship between my screen time data and daily sleep time Based on the data analysis, making behavioral change

Data Collection:
Data collected between Jan 03 to Feb 25.
Screen Time data are collected by built-in Statistics on iPhone, which automatically categorize Apps. Then I manually record the data on Excel.
Sleep Time data are collected by CoSleep Apps and Health Apps Daily Sleep Survey.

Data Cleaning:
Remove rows with NA values
Remove rows with the dates I forgot to record my sleep time data
Convert time data to minutes
For example, transform 7h 8m -> 428.
Join two datasets by date

Variables:
time_slept_min: the total time I slept in a day in minutes [Response Variable]
Total: the total screen time (minutes) on a given date

Screen Time Variables - Categories:
Entertainment, Social, Other_Categories (excluding Safari), Cate_With_Safari

Screen Time Variables - Apps:
Bilibili, WeChat, Safari, Insta, OtherApps

DateType: Categorical, from Monday to Sunday
DayType: Categorical, weekends or weekday

All the code can be viewed in the Appendix

The model has the lowest AIC, BIC, and LOOCV compared to other models.
This model is also relatively interpretable, compared to other models.

Short Analysis:

The intercept of the final model is 433.3990, which means that if we hypothetically assume other attributes to be zero, I expect my sleep time to be 433.39 minutes. In other word, I will expect my sleep time to be 7.22 hours if I did not consider the influence of my daily activities.

A noticable finding in the model is the variation of estimated coefficient values of of DateType. Specifically, the value of coefficients of the DateType has the lowest values on Monday (-130.6597), which means I would expect my sleep time to be 2.18 hours less than the average if we do not consider the influence of other coefficients.

From Monday to Saturday, the value of the estimated coefficients increased steadily, from -130.6597 to 40.0272, but on Sunday, it jumped to -79.5964. A possible explanation would be that most of my assignments are due on Monday and Wednesday, so I tend to experience less sleep time on Sunday, Monday, Tuesday, and Wednesday. After completing those dues, my workload decreased greatly. Thus my sleep time from Thursday to Saturday increased.

From the model, we observed that OtherApps:DayTypeWeekend has the largest estimated coefficient (2.1918) among other factors. This means on weekend, I expect that my sleep time would increase by 2.2 minutes for every minute I spend on OtherApps. Note that this does not infer causality. There are many possible explanations. One might be that the screen time on OtherApps can increased the hormone level of my body, which is associated with improved sleep quality. However, there are also many confounding variables that could influence this finding. The prolonged sleep time may also be influenced by the increased outdoor activities and sun exposure.

The screen time on OtherApps has positive effects on sleep time, and the screen time on Social has positive effects on sleep time during weekdays. The patterns of my sleep time are highly irregular. Based on the results, I believe there is a need for me to set a fixed bed time and strictly enforce it on weekdays.

Improvemnt:

There are rooms for improvement. Firstly, The screen time data is recorded on 24 hour basis; however, I often slept after midnight. We don’t want to measure the data in this way. Instead, we want to record the screen time after wake up and before sleep.

Also, I didn’t wear an Actiwatch, the sleep time measured by my CoSleep App might not be accurate. Poor understanding of device accuracy, systematic error, and uncontrolled comparisons, for example, can lead to misguided trust in devices and misinterpretation of results (Kelley, Lee, and Wilcox, 2017) from article Self-tracking for Mental Wellness- Understanding Expert Perspectives and Student Experiences)

At last, this study does not consider potential confounding variables such as the amount of homework each day and my alcohol assumption. For example, high amount of alcohol assumption can interrupt sleep, and heavy amount of homework and approaching deadlines pushed me to stay up late.

## Load and clean my sleep time data set
daily_sleep_log <- read_csv(file = "/Users/mac/Documents/R_script/Soc325/Project/sleeptime_qingqx.csv")

# Clean sleep time data
sleep_dat <- daily_sleep_log %>%
  group_by(Timestamp) %>%
  summarise(
    Date = str_split(as.character(Timestamp), " ")[[1]][1],
    Date = as.Date(Date) - (1),
    asleep_hour = `What time did you WAKE UP today?` - `What time did you FALL ASLEEP yesterday night?`,
    asleep_hour = str_split(as.character(asleep_hour), " ")[[1]][1],
    asleep_hour = as.numeric(asleep_hour),
    time_slept_min = asleep_hour * 60) %>%
  select(Date, asleep_hour, time_slept_min)

# nrow(sleep_dat)

sleep_dat[51,] <- list(as.Date("2023-2-23"), 6.1, 366)
sleep_dat[52,] <- list(as.Date("2023-2-24"), 8, 480)
sleep_dat[53,] <- list(as.Date("2023-2-25"), 3.1333, 188)

# Clean screen time data

mydat <- as.matrix(mydat)
class(mydat)

time_convert <- function(x) {
  totalmin <- 0
  if (str_detect(x, "h") == TRUE) {
    hr <- str_split(x, "h")[[1]][1]
    
    if (str_detect(x, "m") == FALSE) {
      return(60 * as.numeric(hr))
    } else {
      min <- str_split(x, "h")[[1]][2]
      min <- str_remove(min, "m")
      totalmin <- 60 * as.numeric(hr) + as.numeric(min)
    }
    
  } else {
    totalmin <- str_remove(x, "m")
    totalmin <- as.numeric(totalmin)
  }
  return(totalmin)
}

for (i in 4:13) {
  for (j in 1:dim(mydat)[1]) {
    mydat[j, i] <- time_convert(mydat[j, i])
  }
}

mydat <- as.data.frame(mydat)
mydat$Date <- as.Date(mydat$Date)

mydat <- mydat %>%
  mutate_if(is.factor, as.character)
mydat <- mydat %>%
  mutate_if(is.character, as.numeric)

# head(mydat, 5)

mydat <- mydat %>%
  left_join(x = mydat, y = screentime_datetype, by = "Date")

temp_factor <- factor(mydat$DateType, 
                      levels = c("Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", 
                                 "Thursday", "Friday", "Saturday", "Sunday"),
                      ordered = TRUE)

mydat <- mydat %>%
  mutate(int_day = as.integer(temp_factor),
         # If the day type is weekend, assign 1; else assign 0
         Weekends = case_when(int_day <= 5 ~ "Weekday",
                              int_day > 5 ~ "Weekend"))

Linear Regression, a detailed list

Note: lm1, lm2, lm3 are derived using greedy-algorithm. This list includes all the linear models I tested.

The purpose is trying to understand the importance of influence of each activities on my sleep time, not to predict my sleep time based on my daily activities.

want_col <- c(3, 5, 6, 8:14)
dat2 <- mydat[, want_col]

# full model
lm1 <- lm(`time_slept_min` ~ ., data = dat2)
summary(lm1)  # poor performance
              # Adjusted R-squared:  0.2404 

# step-wise BIC
lm2_aic <- step(lm1, direction = "both", k = log(2))
summary(lm2_aic)      # Adjusted R-squared:  0.2932

lm2_bic <- step(lm1, direction = "both", k = log(53))
summary(lm2_bic)      # Adjusted R-squared:  0.2768 
# poor performance for both models

# full_interacted
lm1_inter <- lm(`time_slept_min` ~ .:DateType, data = dat2)
summary(lm1_inter)
# OVERFITTING 

lm3_aic <- step(lm1_inter, direction = "both", k = log(2))
summary(lm3_aic)      # OVERFIT (PERFECT FIT)

lm3_bic <- step(lm1_inter, direction = "both", k = log(53))
summary(lm3_bic)      # OVERFIT (PERFECT FIT)
# poor performance on both models
